the new math as a marker of the period's political and social ferment. Neither the new math curriculum designers nor its diverse legions of supporters concentrated on whether the new math would improve students' calculation ability. Rather, they felt the new math would train children to think in the right way, instilling in students a set of mental habits that might better prepare them to be citizens of modern society-a world of complex challenges, rapid technological change, and unforeseeable futures. While Phillips grounds his argument in shifting perceptions of intellectual discipline and the underlying nature of mathematical knowledge, he also touches on long-standing debates over the place and relevance of mathematics in liberal education. And in so doing, he explores the essence of what it means to be an intelligent American-by the numbers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEducation and statexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducation and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMathematicsxStudy and teachingxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aMathematicsxStudy and teachingxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aMathematicsxStudy and teachingxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aMathematicsxStudy and teachingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226185019423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226185019.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles